[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] In computing, a **named pipe** (also known as a **FIFO** for its behavior) is an extension to the traditional pipe concept on Unix and Unix-like systems, and is one of the methods of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] The concept is also found in OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, although the semantics differ substantially.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] A traditional pipe is "unnamed" and lasts only as long as the process.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] A named pipe, however, can last as long as the system is up, beyond the life of the process.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Usually a named pipe appears as a file, and generally processes attach to it for IPC.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Instead of a conventional, unnamed pipe, a named pipe makes use of the filesystem.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] It is explicitly created using `mkfifo()` or `mknod()`, and any number of processes can access the pipe by name — one process can open it as a reader, and another as a writer at which point the pipe is instantiated and data can be transmitted through it like on a regular pipe.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] At the point the second shell opens `my_pipe` for writing in the process that will run `cat`, the read-only opening by the first shell is unblocked and both `gzip` and `cat` are then executed concurrently one feeding data to the other through the pipe.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] A named pipe can be used to transfer information from one application to another without the use of an intermediate temporary file.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Without this named pipe, one would need to write out the entire uncompressed version of file.gz before loading it into MySQL.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Writing the temporary file is both time-consuming and results in more I/O and less free space on the hard drive.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] PostgreSQL's command line utility, `psql`, also supports loading data from named pipes.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] A named pipe can be accessed much like a file.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Win32 SDK functions `CreateFile`, `ReadFile`, `WriteFile` and `CloseHandle` open, read from, write to, and close a pipe, respectively.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Unlike Unix, there is no command line interface, except for PowerShell.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Named pipes cannot be created as files within a normal filesystem, unlike in Unix.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Also unlike their Unix counterparts, named pipes are volatile (removed after the last reference to them is closed).
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Every pipe is placed in the root directory of the named pipe filesystem (NPFS), mounted under the special path `\\.\pipe\` (that is, a pipe named "foo" would have a full path name of `\\.\pipe\foo`).
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Anonymous pipes used in pipelining are actually named pipes with a random name.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] They are very rarely seen by users, but there are notable exceptions.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Both programs require the user to enter names in the `\\.\pipe\*name*` form.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Windows NT named pipes can inherit a security context.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] The .NET Framework 3.5 has added named pipe support.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Named pipes can also be used as an endpoint in Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Named pipes are also a networking protocol in the Server Message Block (SMB) suite, based on the use of a special inter-process communication (IPC) share.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] SMB's IPC can seamlessly and transparently pass the authentication context of the user across to Named Pipes.
[src:unix-pipes/named-pipe] Windows NT's entire NT Domain protocol suite of services are implemented as DCE/RPC service over Named Pipes, as are the Exchange 5.5 Administrative applications.
